# The [[elite]] or [[upper crust]] of society.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1803|author=[[w:Maria Edgeworth|Maria Edgeworth]]|title=The Manufacturers|passage=[H]e had been brought up in an extravagant family, who considered tradesmen and manufacturers as a caste disgraceful to '''polite society'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Thackeray Roundabout Papers|passage=[I]n the midst of the company assembled the reader's humble servant was present, and in a very '''polite society''', too, of "poets, clergymen, men of letters, and members of both Houses of Parliament."}}
#* {{RQ:Bulwer-Lytton Parisians|chapter=VI|book=IX|passage={{...|“Pooh! Come in here at least for a few minutes,”—and Bevil drew him up to the door-step of a house close by, where, on certain evenings, a well-known club drew together men who seldom meet so familiarly elsewhere—men of all callings;}} a club especially favoured by wits, authors, and the flaneurs of '''polite society'''.}}
# That portion of society that is especially concerned with [[etiquette]], [[proper]] behavior, and [[politeness]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1892|author=[[w:F. Marion Crawford|F. Marion Crawford]]|title=Pietro Ghisleri|chapter=14|passage=[S]he managed with considerable effort to keep up a sufficient outward semblance of mourning to satisfy the customs and fashions of '''polite society'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1909|author=[[w:P. G. Wodehouse|P. G. Wodehouse]]|title=The Gem Collector|chapter=6|passage=Scenes, Lady Jane had explained—on the occasion of his knocking down an objectionable cabman during their honeymoon trip—were of all things what '''polite society''' most resolutely abhorred.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|date=May 26, 2002|author=Frank Gibney Jr.|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,250016,00.html|title=Can a Church Go Broke?|work=Time|passage=It used to be said that in '''polite society''' one shouldn't discuss sex or money.}}

